Author: Ben Frederickson <github@benfrederickson.com>
Date:   Tue Dec 4 13:58:31 2018 -0800

    Suspend processes before sampling

    Iterating through the python call stack can have issues if we don't first pause
    the process.

    The python stack trace is gotten by traversing a linked list of frame objects
    from the target python processes memory. If the python program returns from a
    function call while this is happening, this seems to result in partial stack
    frames showing up in flame graphs (where the top-level function in the flame
    graph isn't the last function in the stack).

    Fix by suspending the process first before sampling, using ptracee on linux
    TaskSuspend on OSX and NtSuspendProcess on Windows. Also add a 'nonblocking'
    mode that mimics the previous behaviour (not locking the process) for cases
    where having no impact on the target process is more important than having
    totally accurate results.
---
